7. Limitations & Refusal Records
External datasets (ATC Captions, WSPR inference) are Not Ingested. They remain in the "External Bedrock" cell and cannot influence internal claims until they pass a first-class ingestion gate.
	

 
1. Core Structural Units
•	Cell: The primitive, smallest component of the lattice. A cell is an atomic unit of data (e.g., a single GPS coordinate or a SATCOM timestamp) that serves as the building block for witnesses.
•	Node: A discrete point in the state space that binds an event_id to a specific loc_id and time_index (UTC).
•	Edge: A directional or relational link between nodes, often representing a transition or a geodesic path.
•	Lattice: The multi-dimensional grid of nodes and edges where typed observables are mapped. It prevents "axis confusion" by enforcing strict identity for every coordinate.
 
2. Evidence & Witness Taxonomy
•	Witness: A verified state or transition emitted by the pipeline. Unlike a "claim," a witness is an evidence-bound record of a measurement or computation.
•	Witness Stack: The consolidated collection of all witnesses across multiple domains (e.g., TL-M1, MH-001, FIN).
•	Anchor: A high-confidence node used as a fixed reference point (e.g., KLIA Takeoff).
•	Derived Node: A node constructed via an operator (e.g., a geodesic forward solve) that inherits the provenance of its parent.
•	Truth Grade: A scalar value (0.0 to 1.0) representing the reliability of a node or cell based on its source and verification status.
 
3. Decision & Admissibility Logic
•	Admissibility: The status of a data point or claim being permitted to enter the core pipeline.
•	The Precedence Rule ($HALT > INCOMPLETE > PASS$):
o	HALT: A hard stop triggered by unsafe conditions, untyped axes, or verification failure ($V=0$).
o	INCOMPLETE: A state where data is missing or unstable under refinement ($K=0$).
o	PASS: Successful validation; data is promoted to the witness stack.
•	Refusal Record: A formal log entry documenting why a specific input or experiment was denied entry (e.g., "Quarantined: No Corroboration").
•	Quarantine: An isolated storage space for high-noise or "viral" data (e.g., unverified overlays) that is preserved for audit but blocked from influencing conclusions.
 
4. Refinement & Forking
•	Refinement: The process of upgrading the admissibility horizon by adding data, tightening constraints, or increasing the resolution of an operator.
•	Fork: An intentional model variant (e.g., "Measured" vs. "Prior") stored under a composite key to allow for parallel hypothesis testing without overwriting data.
•	Branch: A structural container for ambiguous data (e.g., North/South latitude) that keeps contradictory possibilities alive until refinement collapses them.
•	Bounded-Null: A physical gate where a channel is active but contributes zero (e.g., a moon lux calculation where the elevation is sub-horizon).
 
5. The Triad Grammar ($\Phi/\Theta/\Lambda$)
•	$\Phi$ (States): The domain of realized event steps and ordered sequences (RAW $\rightarrow$ NORM $\rightarrow$ WIT).
•	$\Theta$ (Transitions): The operator domain; the engines of refinement that move data between states.
•	$\Lambda$ (Observables): The measurement domain; the typed axes and scalar fields that allow the lattice to be viewed.
•	Compatibility Predicate ($Compat$): The rule that a domain must provide all three Triad components to be admitted.
 
6. Procedural Constants
•	Scope Lock: A non-causal foundation that prevents the experiment from asserting narrative "intent" or "physical laws" outside of the audited witnesses.
•	Horizon Constant ($P$): An operational parameter (e.g., $18280$) used as a reference period for anchor computations and periodic metrics.
•	Operator Closure: A validation check where an inverse operation must return to the starting value within a defined tolerance (e.g., $DIR + INV \approx 0$).







